y smooth and not much to mention. Differences as follows.\n-\tWith tight HFO in USG we were forced to deviate to Bolivar prior to loading. This adds 20k in port costs, but we were a bit early for laycan so did not affect timing much.\no\tOn that same note, MGO consumption is much higher than expected and $40/mt more expensive than budgeted. Additionally VMS did not account for enough MGO in Suez Canal.\no\tVessel had very good consumption on laden leg. HFO was priced $17/mt less than expected resulting in total bunker savings of $100k compared to precalc.\n-\tLoading in Corpus Christi rather than Houston increases ballast leg slightly, and decreases port costs by $15k\n-\tSuez Canal costs abt $13k less than estimated (We expect a rebate of abt $130k. This is not factored into Intermediate Calculation)\n-\tDischarge port costs $75k higher than estimated with discharge in Mumbai (Nice work chartering team on getting the WCI costs capped at $200k!!!)\n-\tPort operations are completed quickly with not much demurrage to speak of (abt $7k from 0.2 days)"},{"modifiedDate":"2021-12-29T14:29:49.103","modifiedByFull":"Wright, Bryan","remark":"TC Increase \u002B$1.8k with actual arrival figures at Mumbai (Lower Bunker Consumption)"},{"modifiedDate":"2021-12-17T15:23:47.99","modifiedByFull":"Wright, Bryan","remark":"TCE Increase \u002B$2k with actual arrival figures at Suez Canal (Lower bunker consumption)"},{"modifiedDate":"2021-11-19T17:37:30.787","modifiedByFull":"Wright, Bryan","remark":"TC Decrease -$2k on 19 December with discharge port declared Mumbai - Additional $100k port costs"}],"offhireList":[],"tcNumber":null,"tcOutIdEncrypted":null,"tcReletDetail":null}